ðŸ“˜ Artifact #3: proof_forge/pb_theorem/README.md
PoincarÃ©â€“Birkhoff Theorem â€” Proof Forge Specification
Module Tag: PB_Theorem
Zero-Type Class: Topological_Zero, Dynamical_Zero, Symplectic_Zero
Domain: Topological Dynamics, Symplectic Geometry
Objective: Encode the PB theorem proof structure, emphasizing its reliance on invariant measures and topological tension, and demonstrating its fit into the Grand Invariant.
1. Problem Definition
Statement: Every area-preserving homeomorphism of the annulus A = S^1 \times [0,1] that twists the boundaries in opposite directions has at least two fixed points.
Key Geometric Engine:
The map f: A \to A preserves the area form dA. The twist condition imposes non-trivial topology on the dynamics, requiring fixed points to resolve the topological tension.
2. Flow Component: F_{\text{PB}}
Name: Discrete_Twist_Flow
Formal Role: Define the iterative process and the continuous lift required to observe rotation.
Flow Definition
The flow is the discrete iteration of the map f: x_{n+1} = f(x_n).
The dynamics are typically lifted to the universal cover U \approx \mathbb{R} \times [0,1], where the angular coordinate is \theta \in \mathbb{R}. Fixed points in A correspond to intersection points of the lifted graph \text{Graph}(f) with the diagonal \text{Graph}(\text{id}) in U.
Flow Evolution
The flow tracks the angular displacement of points under iteration. The opposite twist condition defines a shear field across the annulus, where f tends to push points on the inner edge "down" (e.g., negative rotation) and points on the outer edge "up" (positive rotation).
Flow Type: Discrete Iteration, Topological Lift, and Shear Field analysis.
3. Energy Component: E_{\text{PB}}
Name: Rotation_Number_Tension
Role: Define the topological and measure-theoretic constraints that must be preserved by the flow, serving as the monotone barrier.
Energy Specification
The energy is the set of Invariants that forbid a fixed-point-free configuration.
 * Twist/Rotation Energy: The required ordering of rotation numbers: \rho_{\text{inner}} \ne \rho_{\text{outer}}. This creates the inherent "tension."
 * Measure Energy: Area preservation (\text{Area}(f(S)) = \text{Area}(S)). This prevents the map from contracting or inflating the annulus, ensuring any deformation must be counterbalanced.
 * Topological Index Energy: For a twist map, the fixed point index \text{Index}(f, A) is constrained by the boundary behavior (often zero, forcing existence of multiple fixed points).
Energy Function Goals
 * Maintain the symplectic structure (area preservation).
 * Enforce the boundary conditions (twist).
 * Any attempt to remove fixed points must violate one of these conserved quantities.
Energy Type: Topological/Invariant Monotonicity Constraint.
4. Singularities Component: S_{\text{PB}}
Name: Dynamical_Fixed_Point_Variety
Role: Define the necessary singularities required to resolve the energy tension.
Singularity Classification
| Type | Description | Behavior |
|---|---|---|
| Good Singularities | Fixed Points (f(x)=x) | Points where the flow stops; the required output of the theorem. |
| Bad Singularities | Fixed-Point-Free Deformation | Hypothetical smooth deformations that satisfy all E constraints but have \text{Index}=0 and no fixed points. |
Objective
The theorem's goal is to prove that the set of Bad Singularities is actually empty due to the constraints of E. The existence of the Good Singularities is forced.
5. Surgery Component: R_{\text{PB}}
Name: Intersection_and_Contradiction_Surgery
Mechanism
To eliminate the Bad Singularities, the proof uses topological surgery on curves and sets:
 * Assume a bad singularity (no fixed points).
 * Construct special curves/arcs connecting the boundaries (e.g., lift curves to the cover).
 * Apply the Flow (F) and Energy Constraints (E) to these curves.
 * Show that the area-preserving, opposite-twist conditions force these curves to intersect in a manner that contradicts the assumption of no fixed points (e.g., forced intersection in the universal cover, or a violation of Brouwer index theorem principles).
Outcome of Surgery
The surgery cuts out the possibility of a fixed-point-free map, proving that the flow evolution must terminate at \ge 2 fixed points.
6. Classification Component: C_{\text{PB}}
Name: Existence_of_Minimal_Fixed_Point_Set
Final Result
The structural constraints force the system into the following classification:
The annulus contains a minimal set of fixed points (at least two) that stabilize the topological flow.

